    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and I'm hitting a wall. We're seeing a slow memory leak where the available RAM gradually exhausts over about 4-6 hours of operation. \n\nI've checked most of the main loops, but I can't find the culprit. Here is a snippet of the telemetry handling class where I suspect something might be going on:\n\n```cpp\nvoid TelemetryManager::processBuffer(const uint8_t* data, size_t len) {\n    // Allocating buffer for incoming packet processing\n    uint8_t* packetBuffer = new uint8_t[len];\n    memcpy(packetBuffer, data, len);\n\n    if (validateChecksum(packetBuffer, len)) {\n        updateSystemState(packetBuffer, len);\n    } else {\n        logError(\"Checksum mismatch\");\n        // Need to ensure this doesn't leak if validation fails\n    }\n\n    // Log the packet size for telemetry\n    this->history.push_back(len);\n    \n    // TODO: Cleanup logic needed here\n}\n```\n\nCan you give me a systematic approach to locating where this leak is coming from in a resource-constrained environment like this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The memory leak in your `TelemetryManager` is almost certainly caused by the `new` allocation on line 4, which is never freed because the `delete` statement is missing entirely. In a resource-constrained automotive ECU, every byte counts, and a slow leak like this will eventually starve the system of RAM, causing it to crash or reboot.\n\nTo fix this, you need to ensure that every `new` has a matching `delete` or `free`, even if the validation fails. Here is a systematic approach to locate and fix the leak in your environment:\n\n1.  **Immediate Fix for the Snippet**: The most obvious culprit is the `new uint8_t[len]` inside `processBuffer`. You must add a `delete[] packetBuffer;` at the end of the function. If you are using modern C++ (C++11 or later), consider switching to `std::vector<uint8_t> packetBuffer(len)` or `std::unique_ptr<uint8_t[]>` to manage the lifecycle automatically and prevent accidental leaks.\n2.  **Static Analysis Tools**: Deploy tools like Valgrind (if the hardware supports it) or specialized static analyzers like Clang Static",
